## Diagnosis

You're right — this is a recurring documentation-lag anti-pattern. A new variant (`solid`) was added to the `Navigation` component's implementation but the playground page was not updated to showcase it. This means the design system's "living documentation" is immediately stale the moment a variant ships.

**Anti-pattern: CAP-016 — Implementation–Documentation Drift**
The component and its documentation/playground exist in separate files with no mechanical coupling, so updates to one don't enforce updates to the other.

---

## Root Cause

The playground is hand-maintained. There is no structural or automated contract between the component's variant definition (the source of truth) and the playground's rendering. A developer can add a variant to the component, ship it, and nothing breaks — the playground just silently omits it.

---

## Fix

### Step 1 — Add `solid` to the playground immediately

**File: `src/app/(frontend)/playground/navigation/page.tsx`**

```tsx
import { Navigation } from '@/components/Navigation'

// ─── Variant registry ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// RULE: Every entry in NavigationAppearance must have a corresponding
// section below. CI will enforce this via scripts/check-playground-coverage.ts
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

const DEMO_LINKS = [
  { label: 'Home',    href: '/' },
  { label: 'Work',    href: '/work' },
  { label: 'About',   href: '/about' },
  { label: 'Contact', href: '/contact' },
]

export default function NavigationPlayground() {
  return (
    <main className="space-y-16 p-10">
      <PlaygroundSection title="appearance="default"">
        <Navigation appearance="default" links={DEMO_LINKS} />
      </PlaygroundSection>

      <PlaygroundSection title='appearance="ghost"'>
        <Navigation appearance="ghost" links={DEMO_LINKS} />
      </PlaygroundSection>

      {/* ── ADDED ── */}
      <PlaygroundSection title='appearance="solid"'>
        <Navigation appearance="solid" links={DEMO_LINKS} />
      </PlaygroundSection>
    </main>
  )
}

function PlaygroundSection({
  title,
  children,
}: {
  title: string
  children: React.ReactNode
}) {
  return (
    <section className="space-y-4">
      <h2 className="font-mono text-sm text-neutral-500">{title}</h2>
      <div className="rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">{children}</div>
    </section>
  )
}
```

---

### Step 2 — Make the variant list the single source of truth

**File: `src/components/Navigation/types.ts`**

```ts
// Every value added here MUST have a playground section.
// The CI script `scripts/check-playground-coverage.ts` enforces this.
export const NAVIGATION_APPEARANCES = ['default', 'ghost', 'solid'] as const
export type NavigationAppearance = (typeof NAVIGATION_APPEARANCES)[number]
```

Update the component to import from this file instead of re-declaring the type inline:

**File: `src/components/Navigation/index.tsx`**

```tsx
import type { NavigationAppearance } from './types'

interface NavigationProps {
  appearance?: NavigationAppearance
  links: { label: string; href: string }[]
}
// ... rest of component
```

---

### Step 3 — Add the CI enforcement script

**File: `scripts/check-playground-coverage.ts`**

```ts
/**
 * Fails CI if any value in NAVIGATION_APPEARANCES is missing
 * from the Navigation playground page.
 *
 * Extend the `CHECKS` array when you add a new component
 * that follows the same pattern.
 */
import fs from 'fs'
import path from 'path'
import { NAVIGATION_APPEARANCES } from '../src/components/Navigation/types'

interface CoverageCheck {
  label: string
  appearances: readonly string[]
  playgroundPath: string
}

const CHECKS: CoverageCheck[] = [
  {
    label: 'Navigation',
    appearances: NAVIGATION_APPEARANCES,
    playgroundPath: 'src/app/(frontend)/playground/navigation/page.tsx',
  },
  // Add future components here ↓
]

let failed = false

for (const check of CHECKS) {
  const fullPath = path.resolve(process.cwd(), check.playgroundPath)

  if (!fs.existsSync(fullPath)) {
    console.error(`✗ [${check.label}] Playground file not found: ${fullPath}`)
    failed = true
    continue
  }

  const source = fs.readFileSync(fullPath, 'utf-8')

  for (const appearance of check.appearances) {
    // Looks for appearance="solid" or appearance={'solid'}
    const pattern = new RegExp(`appearance=["'{]${appearance}["'}]`)
    if (!pattern.test(source)) {
      console.error(
        `✗ [${check.label}] appearance="${appearance}" is missing from the playground.\n` +
          `  File: ${check.playgroundPath}`,
      )
      failed = true
    } else {
      console.log(`✓ [${check.label}] appearance="${appearance}" is covered.`)
    }
  }
}

if (failed) {
  console.error(
    '\nPlayground coverage check failed.\n' +
      'Add the missing variant sections to the playground before merging.',
  )
  process.exit(1)
}
```

---

### Step 4 — Wire the script into CI and `package.json`

**File: `package.json`**

```json
{
  "scripts": {
    "check:playground": "tsx scripts/check-playground-coverage.ts",
    "build": "npm run check:playground && next build"
  }
}
```

**File: `.github/workflows/ci.yml`** (add one step inside your existing job)

```yaml
- name: Check playground coverage
  run: npm run check:playground
```

---

## Codified Rule

Add this to your `CONTRIBUTING.md` or design-system ADR file:

> **Rule DS-001 — Variant–Playground Parity**
>
> Every value in a component's `*_APPEARANCES` (or equivalent variant) constant **must** have a corresponding rendered section in its playground page before the PR can merge.
>
> Enforcement:
> 1. Variants live in `src/components/<Component>/types.ts` as a `const` array — never inlined.
> 2. `scripts/check-playground-coverage.ts` reads that array and asserts each value appears in the playground file.
> 3. `npm run build` and the `ci.yml` `check:playground` step both run this script — a missing section is a build failure, not a code-review suggestion.
>
> To add a variant: update `types.ts` → update playground → CI passes. In that order.

---

## Principle

**Documentation is only trustworthy when it is mechanically coupled to the thing it describes.**
Prose rules and PR checklists erode under deadline pressure. A script that exits with code 1 does not.
